[1] Colombia (Valle del Cauca)
Date: Thu 21 Jan 2010
Source: El Pais (Colombia) [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.elpais.com.co/paisonline/calionline/notas/Enero212010/dengue.html>


The Cali health authorities are on alert for a dengue outbreak that
has doubled the visits [to physicians] because of this disease in
various [medical] assistance centers in the capital. This was
confirmed by the municipal secretary of Health, Alejandro Varela, who
announced that since [1 Jan 2010], the Epidemiological Group tallied
282 cases, of which 123 correspond to the 15-44 year cohort. "We are
facing an increase in the number of patients, and so measures to
identify cases and breeding sites of _Aedes aegypti_ that cause
dengue [transmit dengue viruses] must be taken," Varela explained.

And so the Ministry of Social Protection declared a state of
emergency in the country due to the increase in cases of the disease.
The Secretary of Health warned that in Cali, the citizens must avoid
accumulation of water in their homes, in flower vases, plant pots,
[water] tanks or tires, since 52 percent of the [Aedes aegypti_]
breeding sites originate in these sites.

Up to now, the Comuna 17 (south) is the [area] most affected. In the
current year [2010], 25 cases have been registered and in 2009 there were 370.

The outbreak alerted by the authorities began at the end of last year
[2009]. According to the report from the Secretariat, in the last
quarter of 2009, 2552 cases were recorded, of which 89 percent were
classical dengue and the remaining 11 percent were DHF.

In the different health units in Cali, the medical visits for dengue
have skyrocketed. Jorge Sedano, a specialist in internal medicine in
the Imbanaco Medical Center, said that in this facility the increase
in [the number of] patients from this cause [dengue] have increased
up to 40 percent. "We have seen a gigantic increase in the most
recent months. We do not know if it is due to the weather, but for
certain we are facing a large outbreak," explained the expert.

Most worrisome is that this diseases is having fatal victims. Las
week [week of 11 Jan 2010], the University of Valle Hospital (UVH)
recorded the death of a patient. There is a very high increase in the
outbreak. "The most critical cases are coming to us because many
people do not take precautions. So, when platelets of the body (that
which causes blood to coagulate) are very low, the patient could
die," said Dr Harold Gonzalez, physician assisting in the emergency
room of the UVH. According to the doctor, children are most affected.
Up to 3 children come to the hospital per day, while in a week nearly
4 patients with dengue symptoms are attended to.

In the rest of Valle [department -- state or province equivalent. -
Mod.TY], control [measures] are also being intensified since the
number of reported [cases] in the region increased by 7000 cases last
year [2009]. In 2009 there were 10 171 ill individuals reported,
compared to 3184 in 2008.

The Valle secretary of health, Hector Fabio Useche, has now allocated
250 million [Colombia pesos] [USD 125 913] for prevention of this disease.

Remember to:
- eliminate receptacles that store water for more than a week, such
as tires, clay jars, cans, wash basins, plants in water and barrels,
among others;
- clean your laundry facility each week;
- fill your garden earthen jars, as well as the flower pot plates, with sand.

The _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, which causes dengue [transmits dengue
viruses] can live in a given place up to 2 months. That is the reason
for the recommendation to wash all the water containers, in order to
avoid [mosquito] breeding sites.

