[3] Brazil (Rondonia)
Date: Thu 21 Jan 2010
Source: Rondonoticias [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.rondonoticias.com.br/showNew.jsp?CdMateria=91856&CdTpMateria=7>


The manager of Epidemiology and of the Committee to Combat Dengue of
the state Health Surveillance Agency (AGEVISA), Marcos Ferreira,
explained that the fight against mosquitoes was intensified in
Rondonia, to counter the spread of disease. In 2009, 15 people died,
victims of dengue.

He said later this month [January 2010] AGEVISA will end the spraying
throughout the capital with insecticide to fight the mosquito that
transmits dengue [virus]. The technicians ask for help from the
population so that they should not leave containers where water can
accumulate in their yards.

Marcos Ferreira, explained that the insecticide was composed of a
vegetable base oil and is not harmful to [people's] health. "There
are many people who do not like the smell and close their homes when
they see the fumigation [taking place]. The correct [action] is to
keep the house open, because the insecticide acts only against the
mosquitoes," he said. He explained that AGEVISA decided to combat
dengue through the entire year, to reduce the number of cases.

In 2009, there were 22 689 [dengue] cases recorded in Rondonia, but
the number of illnesses must be greater, because many municipalities
do not tabulate the [case] data.

In Porto Velho, just this month [January 2010] 216 cases of the
disease have been recorded. From January 2009 up to now there have
been 1924 ill individuals [with dengue] in the [state] capital.
Marcos Ferreira recognized that the cases in Porto Velho may be more,
because many people do not go to the health centers [when they are
ill]. We have reports that daily, 500 people go to each health center
in the capital with symptoms of the disease, but generally, it is not
dengue. There are other diseases that produce similar symptoms, such
as malaria, he indicated.

Currently, the incidence of the disease is greatest in Jaru, Porto
Velho, Cacoal, Pimenta Bueno, Vilhena, Ariquemes, Ji-Parana, Rolim de
Moura, and Guajara-Mirim.

--
